WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.000
Chapter One. The Letter. The house was larger than the

00:00:04.000 --> 00:00:08.000
photographs had suggested, and quieter. Margot stood at the end

00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:12.000
of the gravel drive with her suitcase and her messenger

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:16.000
bag and looked at it the way you look at

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:20.000
a sentence in a foreign language — recognizing the shape

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:24.000
without understanding the meaning. Three stories of pale limestone and

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:28.000
dark timber. A slate roof gone silver with age. Windows

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:32.000
that caught the late October light and held it, so

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:36.000
the house seemed to glow faintly from within, though she

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:40.000
knew no one was inside. Or she believed no one

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:44.000
was inside. The letter had said she would be the

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:48.000
first to arrive. She had read the letter eleven times.

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:52.000
She had it memorized the way some people memorize prayers

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:56.000
— not by intention but by repetition, the words wearing

00:00:56.000 --> 00:01:00.000
a groove in her until they were less something she

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:04.000
knew than something she carried. You have been selected. Selected

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:08.000
by whom, for what, on what criteria — the letter

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:12.000
did not say. It named the place, the date, the

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:16.000
duration. One year. It named a stipend that was modest

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:20.000
but sufficient. It named nothing else. Margot had spent four

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:24.000
days researching Eleanora Voss before accepting. She found an obituary

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:28.000
in a regional newspaper — brief, factual, devoid of color.

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:32.000
A mention in the archives of a conservation trust. A

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:36.000
single photograph, badly scanned, of a woman in her seventies

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:40.000
standing beside what appeared to be this house, though the

00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:44.000
angle was different and the trees were smaller. The woman

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:48.000
was not smiling. She was looking at the camera with

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:52.000
her chin slightly raised, as if she had just been

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:56.000
asked something and was deciding whether to answer. Nothing else.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:00.000
No social media, no interviews, no foundation website, no press

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:04.000
releases. Eleanora Voss had lived and died and left behind

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:08.000
a house, a trust, and a set of instructions no

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:12.000
one could quite explain. Margot picked up her suitcase and

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:16.000
walked toward the front door. ... The door was unlocked.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:20.000
This bothered her for reasons she could not have articulated

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:24.000
— something about the vulnerability of it, the openness. She

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:28.000
had spent seven years working in a building where every

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:32.000
door required a badge, where access was tiered and tracked,

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:36.000
where the architecture itself was an argument about who belonged

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:40.000
where. Inside, the hallway was wide and cool and smelled

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:44.000
of beeswax and old stone. The floors were dark oak,

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:48.000
scuffed but cared for. To her left, a doorway opened

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:52.000
into what appeared to be a library. To her right,

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:56.000
a staircase curved upward, its banister worn smooth by decades

00:02:56.000 --> 00:03:00.000
of hands. Straight ahead, at the end of the hall,

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:04.000
a second set of doors stood open to reveal a

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:08.000
kitchen — and beyond it, through tall windows, the green

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:12.000
slope of a lawn descending toward trees. She set her

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:16.000
suitcase down and stood in the quiet. She could hear

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:20.000
the house: the faint tick of wood expanding in the

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:24.000
afternoon warmth, the hum of something mechanical in a distant

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:28.000
room, the wind pressing against the windows on the west

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:32.000
side. These were the sounds of an empty building, and

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:36.000
she had spent enough evenings in her own apartment to

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:40.000
recognize them — the particular quality of silence that exists

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:44.000
when a space built for people contains only one. Her

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:48.000
phone buzzed in her pocket. She took it out, looked

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:52.000
at the notification — a calendar reminder she had set

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:56.000
three months ago, when accepting the residency still felt theoretical:

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:00.000
Arrive at The Keeping House — and put the phone

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:04.000
away. She had told no one about the reminder. She

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:08.000
had told very few people about the residency at all.

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:12.000
Her mother knew, and her former supervisor, and her therapist,

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:16.000
who had said, with the careful neutrality of someone trained

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:20.000
not to project, "That sounds like it could be really

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:24.000
interesting." Margot had wanted her to say more. She had

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:28.000
wanted someone to tell her she was making either a

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:32.000
courageous decision or a terrible mistake, because either would have

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:36.000
been clarifying. Instead, she had been met with the polite,

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:40.000
supportive vagueness she had come to expect from everyone, and

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:44.000
she had gotten in her car and driven six hours

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:48.000
to this house. ... She explored the ground floor the

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:52.000
way she explored everything: methodically, noting details, constructing a mental

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:56.000
map. The library took up most of the east wing

00:04:56.000 --> 00:05:00.000
— floor-to-ceiling shelves of dark wood, a rolling ladder, two

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:04.000
leather armchairs positioned near a window, a reading table with

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:08.000
a green-shaded lamp. The books were eclectic and well-used: novels,

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:12.000
histories, field guides, volumes of poetry, several shelves of philosophy,

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:16.000
a surprising number of cookbooks. She pulled out a copy

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:20.000
of Wendell Berry's essays and found the margins annotated in

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:24.000
a small, precise hand. The same hand, she noticed, had

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:28.000
annotated a novel by Penelope Fitzgerald three shelves away, and

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:32.000
a guide to the native grasses of the central plains

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:36.000
on the shelf above. Eleanora's handwriting. It had to be.

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:40.000
Margot felt the small electric jolt of connection — the

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:44.000
same feeling she got when a pattern emerged from data,

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:48.000
when the noise resolved into signal. She almost took out

00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:52.000
her notebook. Instead, she put the book back and made

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:56.000
herself keep walking. The kitchen was large and well-equipped, with

00:05:56.000 --> 00:06:00.000
a long wooden counter and a range that looked industrial.

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:04.000
Copper pots hung from a rack above the island. The

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:08.000
pantry was stocked — flour, rice, olive oil, canned tomatoes,

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:12.000
dried beans, spices in glass jars with hand-written labels. Someone

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:16.000
had prepared for the residents' arrival. The handwriting on the

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:20.000
spice jars was different from the annotations in the books

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:24.000
— rounder, less precise. The caretaker, presumably. The dining room

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:28.000
held a single long table made of a wood Margot

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:32.000
didn't recognize — something pale and heavily grained, sanded smooth.

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:36.000
It was set for six, though only one place had

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:40.000
a glass of water. She touched the glass. The water

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:44.000
was cool but not cold. Someone had poured it recently.

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:48.000
"You found it, then." Margot turned. A woman stood in

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:52.000
the doorway that connected the kitchen to the dining room

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:56.000
— lean, gray-haired, wearing work boots and a canvas jacket.

00:06:56.000 --> 00:07:00.000
She had the kind of face that was hard to

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:04.000
age: deeply lined around the eyes but clear-skinned, alert. She

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:08.000
was holding a pair of garden shears. "I'm June," the

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:12.000
woman said. "I look after the place." "Margot. Margot Ainsley."

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:16.000
June nodded as though this confirmed something she already knew.

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:20.000
"Your cottage is the third one on the left, past

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:24.000
the birch stand. I put fresh sheets on this morning.

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:28.000
The woodstove draws well but give it a minute on

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:32.000
the damper before you open it all the way." "Thank

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:36.000
you." "Dinner's at seven. I won't be cooking — that'll

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:40.000
be up to all of you — but I stocked

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:44.000
the pantry and there's a garden out back with the

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:48.000
last of the chard and some late tomatoes." She paused,

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:52.000
considering Margot with an appraising directness that felt neither hostile

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:56.000
nor warm. "You're early. The letter said the twenty-eighth." "It's

00:07:56.000 --> 00:08:00.000
the twenty-seventh," Margot said, then added, as if it required

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:04.000
explanation: "I like to arrive before things begin." June made

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:08.000
a sound that might have been a laugh. "Well. You've

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:12.000
got the whole place to yourself tonight. The others start

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:16.000
arriving tomorrow." She turned to go, then stopped. "If you

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:20.000
walk the property, stay on the marked trails until you

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:24.000
know the bluff. The path to the river is steeper

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:28.000
than it looks, and the footing's bad after rain." "Has

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:32.000
it rained?" "It always rains here in October." ... Margot's

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:36.000
cottage was a single room with a sleeping loft, accessible

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:40.000
by a steep wooden ladder. The main floor held a

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:44.000
desk built into the wall below the window, a woodstove,

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:48.000
a bookshelf — empty, waiting — and a chair upholstered

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:52.000
in faded green. The window above the desk faced east,

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:56.000
into a stand of birch trees whose leaves had turned

00:08:56.000 --> 00:09:00.000
the color of old paper. The light through them was

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:04.000
yellow and dappled and moved constantly, so the desk seemed

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:08.000
to float in a shifting field of shadow and gold.

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:12.000
She unpacked with the efficiency of someone who had rehearsed.

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:16.000
Notebooks on the desk — the Leuchtturm for daily observations,

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:20.000
the Moleskine for project notes, the small Field Notes for

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:24.000
things she noticed on walks. Pens in the leather case

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:28.000
her brother had given her when she left her job.

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:32.000
Clothes in the wardrobe: three pairs of pants, five shirts,

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:36.000
two sweaters, a rain jacket. Running shoes. Her laptop she

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:40.000
placed in the desk drawer, face down, as though putting

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:44.000
it to sleep. Then she sat in the green chair

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:48.000
and looked at the trees through the window and tried

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:52.000
to feel what she was supposed to feel. The birch

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:56.000
leaves moved. The light shifted. She registered both. This was

00:09:56.000 --> 00:10:00.000
the problem. She could describe what she felt with great

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:04.000
precision — could locate the tightness in her chest, the

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:08.000
heaviness behind her eyes, the restless energy in her legs.

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:12.000
She could name the feelings, track their frequency, correlate them

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:16.000
with triggers. She had, in fact, done exactly this: a

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:20.000
spreadsheet, updated weekly, mapping her emotional states against sleep, exercise,

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:24.000
caffeine, social interaction, and weather. She had mentioned this to

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:28.000
her therapist once, near the end. "I think I've gotten

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:32.000
very good at monitoring my inner life," she said, "and

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:36.000
I'm not sure that's the same as having one." Her

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:40.000
therapist had been quiet for a long time. Then she'd

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:44.000
said, "What would it look like to stop monitoring?" Margot

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:48.000
hadn't known. She still didn't know. But she had come

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:52.000
here. ... She walked the property before dinner, keeping to

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:56.000
the marked trails as June had instructed. The land was

00:10:56.000 --> 00:11:00.000
larger than she'd expected — the forest began thirty yards

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:04.000
behind the cottages and thickened quickly, hardwoods giving way to

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:08.000
a denser mix of cedar and oak, the canopy closing

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:12.000
overhead until the sky was visible only in patches. The

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:16.000
trail climbed gradually, switching back through limestone outcroppings furred with

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:20.000
moss, until it reached a clearing at the top of

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:24.000
the hill. The clearing held a single bench — rough-hewn,

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:28.000
weathered, bolted to a flat slab of rock. From it,

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:32.000
the view opened suddenly and completely: the river valley below,

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:36.000
the water catching the last of the afternoon light, the

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:40.000
hills on the far side layered in shades of rust

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:44.000
and amber and the deep green of cedars that hadn't

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:48.000
turned. The sky was high and pale and enormous. Margot

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:52.000
sat down. The bench was cold through her jeans. The

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:56.000
wind at this height was steady and carried the smell

00:11:56.000 --> 00:12:00.000
of fallen leaves and something mineral — the limestone, the

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:04.000
river, the particular scent of autumn in country she didn't

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:08.000
know. She reached for her notebook. Stopped. Put her hand

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:12.000
back in her lap. The valley was quiet except for

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:16.000
the wind and, far below, the sound of the river

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:20.000
— not the rush of rapids but a lower, steadier

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:24.000
sound, like breath. A bird she couldn't identify called from

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:28.000
the tree line and was not answered. The light was

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:32.000
changing, the shadows of the western hills beginning their long

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:36.000
reach across the valley floor. She sat there for a

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:40.000
long time. She did not take notes. She did not

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:44.000
check the time. She did not think about the other

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:48.000
residents who would arrive tomorrow, or the project she had

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:52.000
proposed, or the job she had left, or the careful

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:56.000
life she had disassembled in order to be here. She

00:12:56.000 --> 00:13:00.000
sat and she watched the light move across the valley

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:04.000
and she let the cold come into her hands and

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:08.000
her face and she did not name what she felt

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:12.000
because for once — for a few minutes, in a

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:16.000
place she did not know, on a bench someone else

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:20.000
had placed at the exact right spot on the hill

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:24.000
— she did not need to. ... She cooked for

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:28.000
herself that night in the enormous kitchen. Pasta with garlic

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:32.000
and the last of the cherry tomatoes from the garden,

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:36.000
which she found in a basket on the counter with

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:40.000
a note in June's round handwriting: These won't last. Use

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:44.000
them tonight. She ate at the long table, in the

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:48.000
chair nearest the window, with a glass of water and

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:52.000
a view of the darkening lawn. The house settled around

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:56.000
her — those small sounds again, the contractions and expansions

00:13:56.000 --> 00:14:00.000
of old wood, the tick of the radiator in the

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:04.000
hall, the wind finding new angles against the glass. She

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:08.000
washed her plate and her pot and the cutting board

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:12.000
and dried them and put them away. She wiped down

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:16.000
the counter. She turned off the kitchen light and stood

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:20.000
in the dining room in the dark. Six place settings.

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:24.000
One used. Tomorrow there would be more. She walked back

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:28.000
to her cottage along the gravel path, the stars overhead

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:32.000
sharp and numerous in a way she hadn't seen in

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:36.000
years — the specific extravagance of a sky without light

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:40.000
pollution. Her cottage was dark. She lit the woodstove, remembering

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:44.000
June's instruction about the damper, and sat at her desk

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:48.000
while the room slowly warmed. She opened the Leuchtturm to

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:52.000
the first blank page. For a long time she held

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:56.000
her pen above the paper, not writing, feeling the faint

00:14:56.000 --> 00:15:00.000
heat from the stove reach her ankles and then her

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:04.000
knees. The birch trees outside the window were invisible now,

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:08.000
swallowed by the dark, but she could hear them —

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:12.000
the papery rustle of leaves that hadn't fallen yet. She

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:16.000
wrote the date. October twenty-seventh. Below it, after another pause,

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:20.000
she wrote: I am here. I don't know what that

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:24.000
means yet. She closed the notebook and went to bed.

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:28.000
Outside, in the dark, the wind moved through the valley,

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:32.000
and the house held its shape against it, as it

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:36.000
had for a hundred years, as it would — she

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:40.000
was beginning to understand — for a long time after

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:44.000
she was gone. Sometime in the night, she woke to

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:48.000
a sound she couldn't place. It took her a moment

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:52.000
to identify it: gravel, under tires. A car, coming slowly

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:56.000
up the drive. Headlights swept across the ceiling of her

00:15:56.000 --> 00:16:00.000
loft, two long arms of light reaching and retreating. Someone

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:04.000
else was arriving early. She lay still and listened to

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:08.000
the engine cut, the car door open and close, footsteps

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:12.000
on the gravel — heavy, deliberate, the footsteps of someone

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:16.000
carrying something. Then the front door of the main house,

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:20.000
its hinges audible even from here. She pulled the blanket

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:24.000
to her chin and stared at the ceiling and did

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:28.000
not get up and did not look. The house took

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:32.000
its new guest in, as it had taken her, and

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:33.200
the night continued.
